snippet.textDisplay:
We're now Arkwright's corner shop trying to compete with Tesco and Asda.
Arkwright goes to the farmer and asks to buy ten dozen eggs. The farmer gives him a price. "That's too expensive", says Arkwright, "I can't pay that and still sell them at a profit."
"That's the price," says the farmer, "take it or leave it."
Then Tesco comes to the farmer and says, "We want a million eggs and this is how much we'll pay for them."
"I hardly make any profit", says the farmer.
"But you do make a profit and you'll keep on making a profit so long as you sell to us. We'll buy all the eggs you can give us. Take the price we're offering or we'll buy from someone else".
And so people see Arkwright's prices, they decide to get their eggs cheap from Tesco, and Arkwright's little shop goes out of business.

One extremely interesting fact about all this is that in 1986 the UK government, under Margaret Thatcher, was a very influential and enthusiastic protagonist in securing the Single European Act (SEA), which was to set  a deadline of 1992 for the full completion of the single market.

The SEA (1986) involved the following: the removal of barriers to movement of people (Well, I never! 😳); the harmonisation of national standards; rules on how governments buy services and goods; the liberalisation of financial institutions; the setting of more standard value added tax rates, and European business laws.

All things which the UK government now conveniently forgets being instrumental in creating because it fits their narrative of trying to escape the obligations and responsibilities it agreed to with the EU.

Funny, that, don't you think?😏

It was indeed something forced on us really, The EU wasn't very popular at the time it just happened... hearing from people who were part of being against joining back then they saw all this coming they knew it would end bad and that The EU is deceptive and dictative... all we're doing is just paying them to tell us what to do and rule our lives... a lot of politicians were against it too and they carried on talking about leaving throughout Thatchers and Tony Blair's rane too and here we are... they finally did it (thank you).
